                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.113/420.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-17T12:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 17, 1912—12 noon</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Arms, ammunition, as per your April 9, 5 p.m. I am informed that the matter of
                    importation of arms for Guadalajara, Guaymas, and Tampico has been referred by
                    Foreign Office to the governors of Jalisco, Sonora, and Tamaulipas,
                    respectively, whether for the purpose of delaying action or with a view toward
                    ultimate refusal of requests for entry or in good faith the Embassy can not now
                    determine. Consuls at Guadalajara, Hermosillo, and Tampico instructed to make
                    representations directly to the governors.</p>
                <p>Large American emigration during the last few days. The committee of the American
                    colony consequently has more guns than it can dispose of. Consul at Guadalajara
                    advised he can have 150 rifles, with 250 rounds of ammunition each, by paying
                    the duties and price.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
